New: Elasticity can now be combined with two-phase melt transport. The melt
Stokes assembler adds the stored elastic (deviatoric) shear stress as a force
on the solid momentum equation, and can optionally treat the compaction of the
solid matrix as visco-elastic via a new "Reference pore modulus" parameter in
the "Melt settings" subsection (following Keller, May & Kaus, 2013, who define
the porosity-dependent elastic pore modulus K_phi = K_0 phi^(-1/2)); the default
value recovers purely viscous compaction, so existing models are unchanged, so in cells without melt the melt momentum operator reduces exactly
to the incompressible Stokes equation. Because elasticity requires the stress fields to use a
discontinuous discretization, melt transport now permits discontinuous elements
for those stress fields (while other compositional fields and the temperature
must still be continuous). In addition, visco-plastic strain weakening and the
elastic-stress and strain-invariant particle properties now work when the
visco-plastic model is wrapped by the reactive fluid transport model.
<br>
(Ryan Stoner, 2026/07/14)
